'''Christopher Higgins''' (born June 2, 1983) is an [[United States|American]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[winger (ice hockey)|winger]] with the [[Vancouver Canucks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). While playing [[college hockey]], he was selected 14th overall by the [[Montreal Canadiens]] in the first round of the [[2002 NHL Entry Draft]]. He finished a two-year career with the [[Yale Bulldogs men's ice hockey|Yale Bulldogs]], earning [[ECAC Hockey]] Player of the Year honors as a sophomore, before turning professional for the [[2003<U+2013>04 AHL season|2003<U+2013>04 season]]. After two seasons with the Canadiens' minor league affiliate, the [[Hamilton Bulldogs]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL), he joined the NHL in [[2005<U+2013>06 NHL season|2005<U+2013>06]]. He recorded three consecutive 20-goal seasons to begin his NHL career before being traded to the [[New York Rangers]] in June 2009. After brief stints with the Rangers, [[Calgary Flames]] and [[Florida Panthers]], he joined the Canucks in February 2011. Internationally, Higgins has competed for the [[USA Hockey|United States]] in two [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior Championships]] ([[2002 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2002]] and [[2003 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2003]]) and one [[IIHF World Championship|World Championship]] ([[2009 IIHF World Championship|2009]]).

==Playing career==
===Amateur career (1999<U+2013>2003)===
Higgins played high school hockey for two seasons while attending [[Avon Old Farms]], a [[University-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in [[Avon, Connecticut]].<ref name=tsn/> Opting to play in the [[National Collegiate Athletics Association]] (NCAA), he accepted an [[athletic scholarship]] with the [[Yale Bulldogs men's ice hockey|Yale Bulldogs]]. Higgins also considered offers from [[Boston College]] and [[Harvard University]].<ref name=college/> In 2001<U+2013>02, Higgins began a two-year stint with the [[Yale Bulldogs men's ice hockey|Yale Bulldogs]] of the [[ECAC Hockey]] Conference. After recording a team-leading 31 points (14 goals and 17 assists) over 27 games as a freshman,<ref name=entrylevel/> he was named the ECAC Rookie of the Year. He additionally received ECAC All-Rookie and Second All-Star Team honors.<ref name=tsn>{{cite web|title=Chris Higgins|url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/teams/players/bio/?id=2883|accessdate=2011-03-03|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> 

In the off-season, Higgins was selected 14th overall by the [[Montreal Canadiens]] in the [[2002 NHL Entry Draft]]. He became the first ECAC Hockey player to be selected in the first round of the NHL Entry Draft since [[Normand Lacombe]] in [[1983 NHL Entry Draft|1983]] (the [[Buffalo Sabres]] selected him 10th overall).<ref name=college>{{cite news|title=Higgins credits college as key to his success|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=397055|author=Bob Snow|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]|date=2008-12-11|accessdate=2011-03-18}}</ref> Returning to Yale for one more season, he improved to 41 points over 28 games, leading his team in scoring for the second consecutive year.<ref name=entrylevel/> Higgins earned ECAC Player of the Year (co-recipient with [[Cornell Big Red men's ice hockey|Cornell Big Red]] goaltender [[David LeNeveu]])<ref name="nhl notes">{{cite web|title=Chris Higgins - Notes|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/player.htm?id=8470274&view=notes|accessdate=2011-03-18|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}</ref> and First All-Star Team honors; he was also recognized regionally on the NCAA East All-American Team.<ref name=tsn/>

===Montreal Canadiens (2003<U+2013>09)===
Following his sophomore year, he signed a three-year, entry-level contract with the Canadiens on May 22, 2003.<ref name=entrylevel>{{citenews|title=Canadiens agree to terms with 2002 first-rounder Higgins|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/hockey/news/2003/05/22/canadiens_higgins/|accessdate=2011-03-03|date=2003-05-22|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref> Higgins made his NHL debut on October 11, 2003, registering three minutes of ice time in a 4<U+2013>0 win against the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadiens vs. Maple Leafs Boxscore|url=http://canadiens.nhl.com/club/boxscore.htm?id=2003020019|accessdate=2011-03-02|publisher=[[Montreal Canadiens]]}}</ref> Struggling to play his way onto the Canadiens' lineup, he was often made a [[Scratch#Sports|healthy scratch]] in October before being assigned to the team's minor league affiliate, the [[Hamilton Bulldogs]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL), by the end of the month.<ref name=tsn/> He recorded 48 points over 67 AHL games in [[2003<U+2013>04 AHL season|2003<U+2013>04]], ranking fifth in team scoring.<ref>{{cite web|title=2003-04 Hamilton Bulldogs (AHL)|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0007912004.html|accessdate=2011-03-02|publisher=Hockeydb.com}}</ref> Due to the [[2004<U+2013>05 NHL lockout]], Higgins automatically remained in Hamilton and improved to 51 points, ranking third among Bulldogs scorers.<ref>{{cite web|title=2004<U+2013>05 Hamilton Bulldogs (AHL)|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0007912005.html|accessdate=2011-03-02|publisher=Hockeydb.com}}</ref>

The [[2005<U+2013>06 NHL season|following season]], as NHL play resumed, Higgins made the Canadiens' roster out of training camp. He scored his first career NHL goal on October 6, 2005, against [[New York Rangers]] goalie [[Kevin Weekes]] during an away game at [[Madison Square Garden]]. The Canadiens won the contest 4<U+2013>3 in [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ryder's goal lifts Canadiens over Rangers in OT|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=251006013|accessdate=2011-03-02|date=2005-10-06|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He finished the season with 23 goals, ranking seventh among league rookies,<ref>{{cite web|title=Rookie Goals 2005-06|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20062ALLSRSAll&sort=goals&viewName=summary|accessdate=2011-03-02|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}</ref> and 15 assists for a total of 38 points.<ref name=tsn/>

A month into the [[2006<U+2013>07 NHL season|2006<U+2013>07 season]], Higgins suffered a [[ankle sprain|sprained left ankle]] during a game against the [[New Jersey Devils]]. At the time of the injury, on November 4, 2006, he was leading the Canadiens with eight goals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ankle sidelines Higgins|url=http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/sports/story.html?id=478a5d82-93ea-48cc-86d8-2f8c7acdbfeb&k=50800|accessdate=2011-03-02|date=2006-11-07|publisher=''[[The Montreal Gazette]]''}}</ref> Sidelined for 6 weeks,<ref name=tsn/> Higgins was limited to 61 games, though still managed to match his previous season's points total with 22 goals and 16 assists.<ref name=tsn/> Set to become a [[restricted free agent]] in the off-season, Montreal re-signed Higgins to a two-year, [[United States dollar|US$]]3.4 million deal on June 25, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Habs' Higgins, Komisarek back for 2 more years|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/story/2007/06/15/nhl-canadiens-signings.html|accessdate=2011-03-02|date=2007-06-15|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref> Prior to the start of the [[2007<U+2013>08 NHL season|2007<U+2013>08 season]], Higgins was named an [[alternate captain (ice hockey)|alternate captain]] for the Canadiens.<ref name=legends>{{cite web|title=Chris Higgins|url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=20525|accessdate=2011-03-18|publisher=[[Hockey Hall of Fame]]}}</ref> He went on to have a career season with personal bests of 27 goals, 25 assists and 52 points.<ref name=tsn/> On November 11, 2008, Higgins recorded his first NHL [[hat trick]] in a 4<U+2013>0 win over the [[Ottawa Senators]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Higgins pots hat trick as Habs blank Senators|url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/sports/story.html?id=b361438d-e72d-4e91-8660-99f734a04994|accessdate=2011-03-18|date=2008-11-12|work=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|publisher=Postmedia Network|location=Vancouver}}</ref> However, his points total decreased in his fourth NHL campaign with 23 points over 57 games.<ref name=tsn/>

===Post-Montreal (from 2009)===
Coming off what was the lowest statistical season of his career, he was traded by the Canadiens, along with [[Ryan McDonagh]], [[Pavel Valentenko]] and [[Doug Janik]], to the [[New York Rangers]] in exchange for [[Scott Gomez]], [[Tom Pyatt]], and [[Michael Busto]] on June 30, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=4298053|title=Montreal Canadiens acquire Scott Gomez from New York Rangers | publisher =[[ESPN]] | date = 2009-06-30 | accessdate = 2009-07-01}}</ref> A restricted free agent at the time of the trade, he agreed to a one-year, US$2.25 contract with the Rangers six days later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rangers agree to terms with LW Higgins on new deal|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/2009-07-06-2642677672_x.htm|accessdate=2011-03-02|date=2009-07-06|publisher=''[[USA Today]]''}}</ref> He scored his first goal with the Rangers on November 3, 2009, against the [[Vancouver Canucks]], his team's lone marker in a 4<U+2013>1 loss.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers vs. Canucks Boxscore|url=http://rangers.nhl.com/club/recap.htm?id=2009020201|accessdate=2011-03-18|date=2009-11-03|publisher=[[New York Rangers]]}}</ref> His offensive struggles continued in New York (he recorded 15 points in 55 games) and he was subsequently traded to the [[Calgary Flames]] on February 2, 2010. Higgins was dealt, along with [[Ale<U+0161> Kotal<U+00ED>k]], in exchange for [[Olli Jokinen]] and [[Brandon Prust]].<ref name=tsn/> He scored his first goal with the Flames on March 9, an [[empty net goal|empty netter]] in a 4<U+2013>1 win against the [[Detroit Red Wings]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Flames vs. Red Wings Boxscore|url=http://flames.nhl.com/club/recap.htm?id=2009020980|accessdate=2011-03-18|date=2010-03-09|publisher=[[Calgary Flames]]}}</ref> Two days later, he suffered a foot injury that sidelined him for the remaining 14 games of the regular season.<ref name=tsn/> Splitting the season between New York and Calgary, he had 8 goals and 17 points over 67 games.<ref name=tsn/>

Becoming an [[unrestricted free agent]] in the off-season, Higgins signed a one-year, US$1.6 million deal with the [[Florida Panthers]] on July 2, 2010.<ref name=florida>{{Cite news|title=Chris Higgins signs with Florida Panthers|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=5349240|accessdate=2011-03-02|date=2010-07-02|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He had considered re-signing with Calgary, but cited new Florida Panthers general manager [[Dale Tallon]]'s experience as a strong factor for joining Florida (Tallon was largely responsible for assembling the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] team that won the [[Stanley Cup]] the previous season).<ref name=florida/> After 48 games with his new club, he had recorded 11 goals and 23 points.<ref name=tsn/> With the Panthers out of playoff contention late in the season, the team began trading away numerous veterans and core players.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fire sale in Florida at deadline day|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/fire-sale-in-florida-on-deadline-day/article1923753/|accessdate=2011-03-18|date=2011-02-28|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|publisher=Phillip Crawley|location=Toronto}}</ref> At the [[NHL trade deadline]], on February 28, 2011, Higgins was dealt to the Vancouver Canucks in exchange for defensive prospect [[Evan Oberg]] and a third-round draft pick in [[2013 NHL Entry Draft|2013]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=554530|title=Canucks acquire Chris Higgins from the Florida Panthers|publisher=[[Vancouver Canucks]]|accessdate=2011-02-28|date=2011-02-28}}</ref> He scored his first two goals with the club on March 27 in a 4<U+2013>1 win against the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Canucks down Blue Jackets to reach 50 victories for first time|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=359812|accessdate=2011-03-28|date=2011-03-27|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> He completed the season with 13 goals and 28 points in 62 games between Florida and Vancouver.

==International play==
Higgins played in back-to-back [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior Championships]] during his college career. First appearing in [[2002 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2002]], he recorded four goals and two assists over seven games.<ref name=tsn/> He helped the [[United States men's national junior ice hockey team|United States]] qualify for the quarterfinal, where they were eliminated by [[Russia men's national junior ice hockey team|Russia]] 6<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite web|title=2002 IIHF World U20 Championship Results|url=http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/0102/W20/cs/pg000003.htm|accessdate=2011-03-18|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}</ref> The [[2003 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|following year]], Higgins matched his points total with three goals and three assists.<ref name=tsn/> After losing their semifinal to [[Canada men's national junior ice hockey team|Canada]] 3<U+2013>2, the United States lost by the same score to [[Finland men's national junior ice hockey team|Finland]] in the bronze medal game.<ref>{{cite web|title=2003 IIHF World U20 Championship Results|url=http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/0203/W20/0203/scripts/standings/pg000001.htm|accessdate=2011-03-18|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}</ref> 

Higgins made his first international appearance for the [[United States men's national ice hockey team|American men's team]] at the [[2009 IIHF World Championship]]. He scored his only goal of the tournament in a 4<U+2013>3 overtime loss to [[Switzerland men's national ice hockey team|Switzerland]] in the qualifying round.<ref>{{cite web|title=Game Summary|url=http://stats.iihf.com/Hydra/200/IHM200E47_74_3_0.pdf|accessdate=2011-03-02|publisher=International Ice Hockey Federation|format=PDF}}</ref> After losing their semifinal game to [[Russia men's national ice hockey team|Russia]], the United States lost the bronze medal to [[Sweden men's national ice hockey team|Sweden]] by a 4<U+2013>2 score.<ref>{{cite news|title=Game Summary|url=http://stats.iihf.com/Hydra/200/IHM200155_74_3_0.pdf|accessdate=2011-03-18|date=2009-05-10|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]|format=PDF}}</ref>

==Playing style==
Listed at 6 feet (1.83 meters) tall and 203 pounds (92 kilograms), Higgins plays mostly in the style of a [[power forward (ice hockey)|power forward]].<ref name=college/> He is known as a two-way player with good skating, capable of contributing offensively while remaining defensively responsible.<ref name=college/><ref name="q and a">{{cite news|title=Q & A with Chris Higgins|url=http://www.hockeysfuture.com/articles/7281/qa_with_chris_higgins/|accessdate=2011-03-18|date=2004-10-18|publisher=HockeysFuture.com|author=Guy Flaming}}</ref> He has alternated between playing the [[winger (ice hockey)|wing]] and [[center (ice hockey)|center]] positions.<ref name="q and a"/> Early in his career, he was compared to [[Dallas Stars]] forward [[Brendan Morrow]].<ref name="q and a"/>

==Personal==
Higgins grew up in [[Smithtown, New York]], the second eldest among five siblings.<ref name="new canuck">{{citenews|title=New Canuck Chris Higgins aims to reignite career in Vancouver|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/Canuck+Chris+Higgins+admits+have+earn+minutes/4373478/story.html|accessdate=2011-03-02|date=2011-03-02|work=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|publisher=Postmedia Network|location=Vancouver}}</ref> His father, Robert,<ref name=pulse/> is a [[New York City Fire Department|New York City firefighter]] and his younger brother is a [[New York City Police Department|New York City police officer]].<ref name="new canuck"/>

Higgins played on [[minor ice hockey|minor hockey]] teams with former Canadiens teammate [[Mike Komisarek]] and former Flames teammate [[Eric Nystrom]], both of whom he remains close friends with.<ref name=newbie>{{cite news|title=Better known a newbie: Chris Higgins|url=http://communities.canada.com/theprovince/blogs/kurtenblog/archive/2011/02/28/better-know-a-newbie-chris-higgins.aspx|accessdate=2011-03-18|date=2011-02-28|work=[[The Province]]|location=Vancouver|publisher=Postmedia Network}}</ref><ref>{{citenews|title=Higgins: I just want to help|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/hockey/2010/02/02/12716046-qmi.html|accessdate=2011-03-02|work=[[The Toronto Sun]]|location=Toronto|publisher=Sun Media}}</ref> He was a student of [[Lithuanian people|Lithuanian]] hockey coach [[Aleksey Nikiforov]] at hockey camps in his teenage years.<ref name=pulse>{{cite news|title=Matt Gilroy and Chris Higgins|url=http://www.longislandpulse.com/sports-wellness/article/matt-gilroy-and-chris-higgins/|accessdate=2011-03-18|date=2009-11-28|publisher=''[[Long Island Pulse]]''|author=Chris R. Vaccaro}}</ref> Though he grew up on [[Long Island]], Higgins was a Montreal Canadiens fan as a child, following after his father; his favorite players on the team were goaltender [[Patrick Roy]] and captain [[Kirk Muller]].<ref name="q and a"/>

Higgins left home in his Grade 11 year to join the high school hockey program of [[Avon Old Farms]] in [[Connecticut]].<ref name=map>{{cite news|title=Back on the map|url=http://www.nybobcats.com/Page.asp?n=4897&org=nybobcats.com|accessdate=2011-03-18|publisher=[[New York Bobcats]]}}</ref> Following his high school graduation, Higgins was enrolled in [[Yale University]] for two years, majoring in [[political science]] while playing on the school's hockey team.<ref name="q and a"/>

